README.md
     9в†’# Mitt
    11в†’> Tiny 200b functional event emitter / pubsub.
    12в†’
    13в†’-   **Microscopic:** weighs less than 200 bytes gzipped
    14в†’-   **Useful:** a wildcard `"*"` event type listens to all events
    15в†’-   **Familiar:** same names & ideas as [Node's EventEmitter](https://nodejs.org/api/events.html#events_class_eventemitter)
    16в†’-   **Functional:** methods don't rely on `this`
    17в†’-   **Great Name:** somehow [mitt](https://npm.im/mitt) wasn't taken
    18в†’
    19в†’Mitt was made for the browser, but works in any JavaScript runtime. It has no dependencies and supports IE9+.
    20в†’
    21в†’## Table of Contents
    23в†’-   [Install](#install)
    24в†’-   [Usage](#usage)
    25в†’-   [Examples & Demos](#examples--demos)
    26в†’-   [API](#api)
    27в†’-   [Contribute](#contribute)
    28в†’-   [License](#license)
    29в†’
    30в†’## Install
    32в†’This project uses [node](http://nodejs.org) and [npm](https://npmjs.com). Go check them out if you don't have them locally installed.
    33в†’
    34в†’```sh
    35в†’$ npm install --save mitt
    36в†’```
    37в†’
    38в†’Then with a module bundler like [rollup](http://rollupjs.org/) or [webpack](https://webpack.js.org/), use as you would anything else:
    39в†’
    40в†’```javascript
    41в†’// using ES6 modules
    42в†’import mitt from 'mitt'
    43в†’
    44в†’// using CommonJS modules
    45в†’var mitt = require('mitt')
    46в†’```
    47в†’
      в†’вЂ¦
    56в†’## Usage
    58в†’```js
    59в†’import mitt from 'mitt'
    60в†’
    61в†’const emitter = mitt()
    62в†’
    63в†’// listen to an event
    64в†’emitter.on('foo', e => console.log('foo', e) )
    65в†’
    66в†’// listen to all events
    67в†’emitter.on('*', (type, e) => console.log(type, e) )
    68в†’
    69в†’// fire an event
    70в†’emitter.emit('foo', { a: 'b' })
    71в†’
    72в†’// clearing all events
    73в†’emitter.all.clear()
